social_posts.post_text: Y’all asked for it: 5 things I WOULD do as an ER Veterinarian. (number 5 is my fav 🥰)

It’s now 2023, and we are what? Not taking our dogs to dog parks. That’s right 👌🏼⁣
⁣
Between the dog fight/bite wounds, infectious diseases and parasites, and extremely poor social interactions, dog parks may keep us ER vets in business, but we literally don’t want that. ⁣
⁣
The most common question I get when I tell people to stay away from dog parks is “but then how will they socialize?!” Surprisingly enough, your pup does not NEED to socialize with random poorly behaved dogs without proper structure and boundaries. If you want play dates for your dog, meet up with a friend that you know has a fully vaccinated, well behaved dog and let them play together. ⁣
⁣
The second most common question is “but how will I get their energy out?!” Mental stimulation and structured walks are MUCH better methods of tiring your pup out than letting them join the dog park greaser gang. Plus those structured walks get you and I moving as well! ⁣
⁣
Any other questions I haven’t answered? Leave them below!
Also goes for Zeus the Dane, Athena the pittie, Cooper the Golden, and any dog named Lucky who is absolutely the unluckiest dog alive 🙃
Sir, I just need to know what kind of food your dog eats. #veterinarian #dogsofinstagram #mentalhealth

Urinary Obstructions 💀 ⁣
⁣
Yep, it’s exactly what you’d expect with a name like that. But why, what, how?
⁣
One of the most common true emergencies we see in the ER is urinary obstructions in male cats. Yes, it can happen in females and/or dogs, but male cats have the unique ability of obstructing their bladder for many times no gosh darn good reason. ⁣
⁣
True, it can be because of an infection (rarely unless they’re older than 10), or big ol’ bladder stones, most of the time it’s the tiniest amount of gritty material, mucous, or inflammation that causes them to obstruct. And if I didn’t make it clear earlier, THIS IS A MEDICAL EMERGENCY 🚨 ⁣
⁣
So first, what are some ways to prevent this from happening?⁣
⁣
1. Increase moisture content in their diet. Adding wet food, & encourage drinking with water fountains.
⁣
2. Plenty of litter boxes! Research shows you should have one litter box per cat PLUS ONE to reduce potty stress.⁣
⁣
3. Reduce stress in the household. Cats are weird little creatures, and can literally cause urinary changes due to stress. Things like lots of pets, not enough litter boxes, or they just don’t like the new couch you bought can trigger them 😅 ⁣
⁣
That’s all well and good, but how do you KNOW your cat may be having this issue? After all, we all know cats are stoic and love to hide things until they’re a huge problem. So some signs they may be experiencing early signs of urinary tract changes/inflammation include:⁣
⁣
•Urinating outside of the box⁣
•Going in and out of the box frequently ⁣
•Blood in the urine ⁣
•Decreased appetite ⁣
•Vomiting⁣
•Howling or crying when they urinate ⁣
⁣
If you notice any of these signs, this is the kind of thing NOT to wait on and see if it gets better. Get them checked out ASAP. Better to catch it too early than too late. And as a final little insider tip, I never recommend leaving your cats home with automatic food and water for a long weekend away. Too many times I’ve had owners come home to a very sick, dying or even deceased cat because no one was home to monitor their potty habits and they got stressed out by their person leaving. Just not worth the risk in my opinion 💔⁣
⁣
Questions? Leave them below!

“Hey doc, my dog is vomiting, but I don’t know if it’s really an emergency…”⁣⁣
⁣⁣
One of the MOST common calls I get on an ER shift hands down, are owners trying to figure out if their pet vomiting really warrants a trip into the ER in the middle of the night or if they can wait it out and either see their own vet or maybe it’ll just work itself out. So here are a few tips for knowing how worried you should be. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
First and foremost, without a doctor seeing your animal, we have absolutely no idea how sick they truly are. What you might see as *only* vomiting, we might see a dog in shock, icteric, or a number of other red flags. So it is never wrong to get a vomiting pet checked out!! Best case scenario, they just need a little supportive care to get through it, but in worst case maybe we’ve caught something early. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
A few major warning signs you need to seek care right away:⁣⁣
⁣⁣
• your pet is lethargic along with the vomiting⁣⁣
• ANY amount of blood in the vomit⁣⁣
• They refuse to eat (especially a food motivated pet) or can’t hold their food down⁣⁣
• Diarrhea with the vomiting ⁣⁣
• They’re not holding water down⁣⁣
• They’re regurgitating. This means there is no active heaving of their belly, but it’s just “falling out” of their mouth if you will.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Ultimately, I always recommend a vomiting pet be seen, but those things might help you determine if you need to haul you and your fur baby out of bed in the middle of the night to come see the emergency team, or if you might be able to wait it out until morning. And if you’re really not sure, you can always give your local ER a call and chat with the team to see what they recommend. Like I always say, if you’re concerned, I’m concerned. Better to bring them in. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Featuring Maui! One of my favorites from this month who underwent surgery for an intestinal obstruction, who, other than intermittent vomiting for a couple of weeks seemed perfectly fine! Dad said he even had the zoomies the day before surgery, and he never would have guessed how sick he really was! It just goes to show, you can never be too safe! 💕⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Questions or a 🚩 you think I missed? Drop them below!

Microchips play a huge role in reuniting pets that have gone missing and their family members. If you find a lost animal, any vet office can scan that animal for a chip BUT if it’s not registered to an owner, or not up to date with your most accurate information it will do us no good! Make sure your pet is microchipped and your info is as up to date as possible! #veterinarian #petstagram #petsafety #vegambassador

SNAKE SEASON 🐍⁣
⁣
Y’all. It’s here. I mean we all knew with warmer weather came the creepy crawlies, but it’s been confirmed over and over this week that the snakes are out in full force.⁣
⁣
The most common venomous snakes in North America are the cottonmouth, copperhead, and various types of rattlesnakes. Each venom acts in its own way, but the common denominator is when bit by one, your pets NEED veterinary cares. STAT.⁣
⁣
Unfortunately there is no good remedy at home that can combat these bites. The severity ranges from local pain and swelling, to gruesome wounds, bleeding disorders, shock and death. Time is of the essence with these kiddos so getting them seen quickly is key. ⁣
⁣
A few tips for preventing snake bites from happening:⁣
⁣
• Hiking during warmer months should be on leash to prevent snoots from venturing into underbrush or off path and into our snake-y friends homes. ⁣
• Accompany your pets outside for bathroom breaks, ESPECIALLY the last one of the night, and carry a flash light to look around. ⁣
• Make noise anywhere you go when you’re outside so they hear you coming and can do their best to avoid you.⁣
• Check outdoor water buckets/bowls for critters before letting your pets approach.⁣
⁣
And last but not least do NOT suck venom out of a snake bite! ⁣
⁣
If your pet does end up getting bit and your not a snake expert, try to get a photo (or the snake) so the emergency team can identify it and make sure treatment options are best laid out for that snake! Any questions? Leave them below!

This is a reminder that on a holiday weekend:⁣⁣
⁣
• Your dog should be on a leash. Period.⁣⁣
• Corn cobs should be consumed and then IMMEDIATELY put in a trash can outside of the house. ⁣⁣
• Dogs and lawn mowers (or other motorized vehicles) should never mix.⁣⁣
• Your dog doesn’t know it’s a holiday, they don’t need a plate at the barbecue. ⁣⁣
• Pet Poison Control’s phone number is 800-213-6680. ⁣⁣
• The veterinary emergency room WILL BE PACKED. Bring a book, bring some snacks, and bring a positive attitude. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Happy Labor Day 🫶🏻 stay safe out there, kids. ⁣⁣

“Will pet insurance cover this?” ⁣
⁣
“Oh you have pet insurance?” ⁣
⁣
“No, but if we get it now, it’ll cover it right??”⁣
⁣
I can’t tell you how many times I’ve had this exact conversation with owners. The unexpected happens, like in this bby Dane’s case, when he’s only 10ish weeks old and ends up in the emergency room after the owners have had him the shortest while. The bill is astronomical, or it just so happens to come at the wrong time in their life, and the owners are grasping for whatever they can to make it happen.⁣
⁣
If I have one piece of advice for any pet owner, new puppy or not, have a financial plan in place for WHEN not IF disaster strikes. ⁣
⁣
Pet insurance will NOT cover a pre-existing condition. If you’re in a place where you need it, it’s too late. ⁣
⁣
Now pet insurance is not fitting for everyone, so if nothing else a health savings account that had a set aside amount for emergency care is absolutely recommended. For reference, emergency surgery can range anywhere from $3,000 - $10,000 (or more), and hospitalization can be anywhere from $1,500-3,000 per 24 hours. So when we talk about a savings account, we mean a sAviNgS aCcOuNt 🙃⁣
⁣
For a more in-depth pet insurance chat - check out my pet insurance highlight & feel free to leave questions below! #veterinarian #vegambassador #greatdane

BOO 👻 ⁣
⁣
Nothing scarier than a vicious puppy attack to start off your Halloween celebrations! ⁣
⁣
A couple tips to keep you and your ghouls out of the ER tonight! ⁣
⁣
- Sugar free candy (anything sweetened with Xylitol) gets consumed or tossed out (in an outdoor trash ideally) as soon as trick or treat fun is over! Xylitol is extremely toxic to dogs and can lead to rapid drops in blood sugar and liver failure 🎃 ⁣
⁣
- Trick or treat bags get PUT AWAY in a cabinet faraway from prying snouts! Don’t let anyone (child or pup alike) sneak a midnight snack while you’re fast asleep!⁣
⁣
- If any costumes are made with string/tinsel (think baby TSwift sparkly tassels, flapper dresses, etc) that might appeal to your kitty friends - make sure those get picked up and put away at the end of the night! Nothing a cat loves more than swallowing string whole & causing a world of problems! ⁣
⁣
- Pet Poison’s phone number is 800-213-6680 if your pet DOES get into anything and you need to know if a trip to the ER is worth it. ⁣
⁣
Anything I missed?? Make sure to share below!! Happy Halloween, friends!! Are your pets dressing up? PLEASE tell me below! 🫶🏻👻 #vegambassador #veterinarian #kingcharlescavalier

Good news!! Fluffy’s tests are all normal! ⁣
⁣
“Alright doc… so what’s wrong with ‘em?” ⁣
⁣
Your dog, cat, or hamster is sick. You take them into the vet, and they tell you they want to run some tests to get to the bottom of it. They’re your baby so of course you say yes. You’ve spent a pretty penny of this week’s paycheck, and everything comes back normal. What now? ⁣
⁣
Unfortunately, our pets can’t speak to us (I know, SHOCKER) and there are many MANY times we don’t get a clear cut answer when our pets are sick. Which believe me, frustrates us just as much as it frustrates you as a pet owner. ⁣
⁣
But the silver lining is with diagnostics and testing we have ruled OUT so many big scary things, and most times when that’s the case we get to treat your pets symptoms and see them improve. Other times, when we’ve done all the things, and maybe we’re not improving, our goal is to get them to a specialist who might be able to find things we can’t. ⁣
⁣
In the emergency room, we have three golden rules:⁣
⁣
1. Keep them alive until morning⁣
2. Alleviate suffering ⁣
3. Find an answer or get them to someone who can⁣
⁣
Many times we do get an answer, but in the event we don’t, just remember how many things AREN’T happening to your pet and how much information we obtain from normals! As a vet, I’d always rather normal blood sugar vs a diabetic, or boring x-rays vs an intestinal obstruction. So until someone invents Dug the talking dog’s collar, we’ll be here running tests and wishing all day long for normals! 🫶🏻
